ybe I need to use non-JDK types with reflection metadata to trigger tracking. JDK classes might resolve without dynamic access metadata, and perhaps the tracker only records certain types of access. Still, the tracked API is the exact call site, but JDK classes could be exempt. Native image build may fold string constants like `\\\\\\\"java.util.LinkedHashMap\\\\\\\"` into class literals, removing the call.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating class handling for native image**\\\\n\\\\nI see that the focus is on managing `TypeHolder` and considering `ResolvableType`. I'm wondering if using `Class.forName` could cause issues in native image due to class availability. The user didn't report any runtime errors after the compile fix, which is good. Since the task is about test coverage, I think adding test resource metadata for `ResolvableType` might be okay. I’ll avoid unrelated metadata and focus on active class handling instead. We might also consider switching to runtime-created class names to prevent compile issues. Let's keep refining this approach!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Refining class name resolution**\\\\n\\\\nI’m considering changing the current file to replace `quotedClassName(Class<?> type)` with `quotedClassName(resolvableClassName())`. I’m implementing a test to ensure top-level classes resolve from string values correctly. I’ll use a function to get a class name dynamically. \\\\n\\\\nI wonder if even using a new instance might be treated like a constant in native image evaluations. While runtime access should be fine, I’m thinking adding methods that use `System.nanoTime()` or string splitting could confirm the dynamic nature. I might also try constructing class names from elements to further ensure they aren’t constant. Let’s sort this out!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Optimizing class retrieval**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking that using `new ResolvableType().getClass().getName()` is a better approach because it's determined at runtime and doesn't rely on direct reflective loading. This might help avoid potential issues during native image evaluations, ensuring the class name is correctly accessed without giving rise to reflection pitfalls. It feels like a more efficient and safer way to handle class names, especially in this context. Let's implement this change for a smoother runtime operation!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_jQzs24KZZL7WiWikbK8OSGTc|fc_0ee5382eb719f5cb0169f030aba5d4819d80e42a73f2828c94\", \"name\": \"edit\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/com.fasterxml.jackson.jr/jackson-jr-objects/2.21.0/src/test/java/com_fasterxml_jackson_jr/jackson_jr_objects/SimpleValueReaderDynamicAccessTest.java\", \"edits\": [{\"oldText\": \"    void resolvesTopLevelClassesFromStringValues() throws Exception {\\n        Class<?> resolved = JSON.std.beanFrom(Class.class, quotedClassName(ResolvableType.class));\\n\\n        assertThat(resolved).isSameAs(ResolvableType.class);\\n    }\\n\", \"newText\": \"    void resolvesTopLevelClassesFromStringValues() throws Exception {\\n        String className = resolvableClassName();\\n\\n        Class<?> resolved = JSON.std.beanFrom(Class.class, quotedClassName(className));\\n\\n        assertThat(resolved.getName()).isEqualTo(className);\\n    }\\n\"}, {\"oldText\": \"    void resolvesClassTypedBeanPropertiesFromStringValues() throws Exception {\\n        TypeHolder holder = JSON.std.beanFrom(TypeHolder.class,\\n                \\\"{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\" + quotedClassName(ResolvableType.class) + \\\"}\\\");\\n\\n        assertThat(holder.type).isSameAs(ResolvableType.class);\\n    }\\n\", \"newText\": \"    void resolvesClassTypedBeanPropertiesFromStringValues() throws Exception {\\n        String className = resolvableClassName();\\n\\n        TypeHolder holder = JSON.std.beanFrom(TypeHolder.class,\\n                \\\"{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\" + quotedClassNa