e_Hc8Fc0xX_Joxw3nvVoqbiXgZM2ueoigTiDZj8t9Z0vcrQeY_zP2bHwTA90nSne-ceYCLmKRL-YBQOrQy_YsgNsjCs8-oq3t_RCWC7ZVGkQigDFyBGldmA3_th7TlGqIm_Ze8ElsBCttLxmAlcs_um31FhrZzbzPCgqssMeP_Ke8fVLVUUGJzAWa_Ws2PFQmRdDCkGyL0l9_AMIBbC4NU7S8qESaq5XeHZiEeL3IfvTg58fhzJiVLSHEPMdeQHwOXngPHyZ9ITkDA3-ffFAhMut6eYG8PHG9oRPcTfixUAWctDLPFZnBurMcbsNPgw_0-pxgwIW3XFUTj7hntFawv-K3MQ==\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating inner class issues**\\\\n\\\\nI'm wondering if there's an issue because `ResolvableType.class.getName()` contains a '$' for the inner class. Class.forName handles this differently, but the rule prohibits '$' in test class names, not nested classes. Still, could this cause metadata issues? The native-image metadata file only lists entries for `TypeHolder`, not for `ResolvableType`. Tests might pass on JVM, but the user didn’t mention if they re-ran after the compile fix or if the dynamic coverage is still none. I need to consider using only JDK classes since they’re accessible.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Analyzing coverage tracking issues**\\\\n\\\\nSo, it ran, and it's indeed not covered. I'm starting to think that using `Class.forName` on JDK classes isn't tracked because of how native image handles them. Maybe I need to use non-JDK types with reflection metadata to trigger tracking. JDK classes might resolve without dynamic access metadata, and perhaps the tracker only records certain types of access. Still, the tracked API is the exact call site, but JDK classes could be exempt. Native image build may fold string constants like `\\\\\\\"java.util.LinkedHashMap\\\\\\\"` into class literals, removing the call.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating class handling for native image**\\\\n\\\\nI see that the focus is on managing `TypeHolder` and considering `ResolvableType`. I'm wondering if using `Class.forName` could cause issues in native image due to class availability. The 